]\n| occupation  =Lawyer\n}}\n'''David Alan Trott''' (born October 16, 1960) is the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Michigan's 11th congressional district]]. He is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nTrott was born in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://info.cqrollcall.com/rs/cqrc/images/CQNews_NewMemberGuide2014.pdf|title=Guide to the New Congress|publisher=[[Roll Call]]|accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/article/533669|title=Michigan-11: Dave Trott (R)|website=Nationaljournal.com}}</ref> He graduated from [[Cranbrook Schools|Cranbrook]] in 1978, and obtained a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1981. He graduated from the [[Duke University School of Law]] in 1985, receiving his [[Juris Doctor]].<ref name=\"Crain's\">{{cite news|last=Halcom|first=Chad|title=Farmington Hills exec David Trott declares candidacy for Bentivolio's U.S. House seat|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20130904/NEWS/130909947/farmington-hills-exec-david-trott-declares-candidacy-for-bentivolios|accessdate=September 11, 2013|newspaper=Crain's Business Detroit|date=September 4, 2013}}</ref> Trott was a member of the [[Bingham Farms]] Village Council from 1987-1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dave Trott|url=https://www.gop.com/leaders/congressman-dave-trott-mi|website=GOP.com|publisher=Republican National Committee}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTrott is the chairman and CEO of Trott & Trott PC, which represents banks and lenders in homeowner foreclosure and bankruptcy litigation. He is the owner of Attorneys Title Agency LLC and its subsidiaries. Trott is also the co-owner of Dietz Trott Sports & Entertainment,<ref name=\"Crain's\"/> and owns Trott Recovery Services.<ref name=Pres>{{cite news|last=Korte|first=Gregory|title=Romney super PAC supporter has ties to Freddie and Fannie|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/politics/story/2012-02-02/mitt-romney-super-pac-trott-and-trott-freddie-mac-fannie-mae/52939706/1|accessdate=September 11, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 3, 2012}}</ref> Trott has also served as chairman and CEO of NDeX, and has been affiliated with Detroit Legal News Publishing, the U.S. Foreclosure Network, and [[First American Financial Corporation]]. Trott's legal career and impact on the community was profiled on the front page of the ''[[Detroit Free Press]]'' on May 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20140518/NEWS06/305180087/david-trott-foreclosure-mortgage-housing-real-estate-michigan|title=U.S. House candidate David Trott made millions in mortgage crisis|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref>\n\nTrott has served on the boards of the [[University of Michigan]], On My Own, the Detroit Country Day School, The Community House, and the Karmanos Cancer Institute.<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title=David Trott|url=http://www.forbes.com/profile/david-trott/|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> He is additionally a partner of 23 energy companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/public_disc/financial-pdfs/2013/9103183.pdf |format=PDF |title=United States House of Representatives : David A. Trott |website=Clerk.house.gov |accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref> He was a candidate for the [[Oakland Community College]] Board of Trustees in 2012.\n\nTrott chairs the [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]] Lincoln Day Dinner, an important GOP fundraising event.<ref name=Oakland>{{cite news|last=AlHajal|first=Khalil|title=U.S. Rep. Kerry Bentivolio faces primary challenge from Oakland County Republican David Trott|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2013/09/us_rep_kerry_bentivolio_faces.html|accessdate=September 11, 2013|newspaper=MLive|date=September 4, 2013}}</ref> Trott was a major donor to the [[Republican National Committee]] and the presidential campaigns of [[John McCain]] and [[Mitt Romney]].<ref name=\"Pres\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2014 election===\nOn September 4, 2013, Trott announced his candidacy for [[Michigan's 11th congressional district]], challenging incumbent freshman Congressman [[Kerry Bentivolio]].<ref name=\"Crain's\"/> Former Michigan State Senate Majority Leader Mike Bishop, Wayne County Commissioner Laura Cox, former Congressional candidate Rocky Raczkowski, and Republican Committeewoman Ronna Romney McDaniel were announced as his campaign co-chairs. Both the Michigan Chamber of Commerce and the [[United States Chamber of Commerce]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/u-s-chamber-endorses-kerry-bentivolios-gop-challenger/|title=U.S. Chamber Endorses Kerry Bentivolio's GOP Challenger|work=At the Races|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref> endorsed Trott's campaign, joining more than 350 other individuals and elected officials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trottforcongress.com/endorse-dave-trott/endorsements/|title=List of Endorsements|work=Dave Trott for Congress|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref>\n\nOn May 27 MIRS \u2013 Michigan Information and Research Service published the results of an initial Republican primary poll for the 11th Congressional District which showed incumbent Kerry Bentivolio at 33% to Trott's 21%, with a large portion of the district undecided.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirsnews.com/alert.php?alert_id=1782 |title=?? |website=Mirsnews.com |accessdate=2015-12-19}} {{subscription required|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\nTrott enjoyed a significant advantage in resources over his opponent throughout the campaign, with more than $1 million in the bank following the first quarter of 2014, compared to Bentivolio's $130,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20140416/NEWS15/304160194/Campaign-financial-reports-show-lots-activity-tough-race-11th-district|title=Bentivolio reports $130,000 in campaign war chest for Congress to Trott's $1M|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref> According to Federal Election Campaign filings Trott had personally contributed over $2,400,000 to his own primary run and outspent the incumbent approximately 20:1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/fecviewer/CandidateCommitteeDetail.do|title=Committee/Candidate Search|website=Fec.gov|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20140915/POLITICS/309150086/Bentivolio-seriously-considering-write-campaign |accessdate=February 4, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019175740/http://www.detroitnews.com/article/20140915/POLITICS/309150086/Bentivolio-seriously-considering-write-campaign |archivedate=October 19, 2014 }}</ref> The congressional primary election was held on August 5, 2014 in which he defeated Bentivolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20140805/NEWS06/308050217/Congress-11th-Bentivolio-Trott|title=Michigan news|work=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref> Bentivolio tried to initiate a write-in campaign for the November 2014 election to run against Trott and Democrat Bobby McKenzie to continue serving the people of Michigan in Congress, however that effort failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2014/10/02/bentivolio-write/16605253/|title=Bentivolio plans write-in campaign for Congress|author=Chad Livengood and Steve Pardo|publisher=The Detroit News|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration and Border Security|Subcommittee on Immigration and Border Security]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law|Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law]]\n\n===2016 election===\nTrott won re-election with 53% of the vote against Democrat Anil Kumar who had 40% of the vote, Libertarian Jonathan Ray Osment with 3%, and Independent [[Kerry Bentivolio]] with 4%.<ref>[http://uselections.com/mi/mi.htm]</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nTrott is [[pro-life]], supports [[school choice]] programs, supports [[gun rights]], and is opposed to [[same-sex marriage]], but believes that the issue should be left to the states to decide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwzLZM1Fpa0 |title=Dave Trott evasive on Marriage Equality question |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-06-29 |accessdate=2015-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://trottforcongress.com/ Dave Trott for Congress]\n*[http://www.trott.house.gov/ Official U.S. House site]\n{{CongLinks | congbio = T000475 | votesmart = 152477 | washpo = | govtrack = | opencong = | cspan = davidtrott| ontheissuespath =  | congress = david-trott/T000475 | legistorm =  | fec = H4MI11097 | opensecrets =  | followthemoney = | nyt =  | findagrave = }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| before = [[Kerry Bentivolio]]\n| start=January 3, 2015\n| state=Michigan\n| district=11}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Norma Torres]] <br><small>D-[[California]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=421st}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Walker (North Carolina politician)|Mark Walker]]<br><small>R-[[North Carolina]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{MI-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Michigan Representatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trott, Dave}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Michigan Republicans]]\n[[Categ